title: Does Hitler have any known living relatives? - Quora

response.answer_text: THIRTY-NINE living relatives of Adolf Hitler have been discovered by a customs official and a journalist who claim to have decoded the Nazi dictator's DNA. Analyzing forgotten cigarette butts in a smalle village in lower Austria, a used paper serviette in a New York fast-food restaurant and the seals of letters sent over 30 years ago from northern France, Marc Vermeeren and Jean-Paul Mulders said they had traced all known living relatives of the Fuehrer for the first time. As well as three living in America, whose existence has been reported previously, they claim to have tracked down 36 others who still live in the wooded area of Austria where Hitler was born. Mr Vermeeren, a Belgian customs official, and Mulders, a journalist for Belgian newspaper Het Laaste Nieuws, said three great-grandchildren of Hitler's father, Alois, lived on Long Island, outside New York, under the false name Stuart-Houston. They are descendants who left Germany to escape the Nazis. Louis and Brian Stuart-Houston share a little wooden house in East Patchogue, where they work as gardeners, while Alexander is a retired psychologist who helps Vietnam veterans. The Belgians said they had watched them for seven days and nights, following 60-year-old Alexander to a fast-food restaurant where he disposed of a paper serviette after eating fried chicken that they retrieved and later matched with ''DNA of Hitler that we keep in a sealed, armoured chest''. The cigarette butts came from Hitler relatives in Austria. The American relatives have agreed not to have children to extinguish the saga of Hitler and stop living in fear, but have promised to publish a book before they die.

According to a recent report, some of Hitler's relatives have been living on Long Island for decades. Hitler's great-grandchildren Louis, Alexander, and Brian Stuart-Houston, the last descendants of Hitler's father, live in the suburbs of New York, according to the German publication Bild, which recently tried to talk to them.  FoxNews writes that the three men are the sons of Hitler's nephew, William Patrick Hitler, who was born in Great Britain, his father being his half-brother Alois Hitler Jr. Alois emigrated to Dublin at the age of 14, where he worked as a waiter. William returned to Germany in 1929 to take part in the Nuremberg Rally. He then returned to Britain, where he began giving press interviews, being considered Hitler's "English nephew" and then summoned to Berlin by an angry Fuhrer. "What did you say in the paper?" Who gave you permission to talk about my private affairs? "Hitler would have asked, as William's mother, Brigid, says. "No one is allowed to talk about my private life in the newspaper. I never said a word he could use, and now he's a "grandson" who tells them all the miserable details they want to know, "William's mother recalled. William then traveled to New York, where he continued to give lectures on his family, and later enlisted in the army to fight in World War II. After the war, he moved to Patchogue, with his German-born wife, and changed their initial name to Hitler and then to Stuart-Houston, according to Bild. The man died in 1987, at the age of 76, and now two of his sons have refused to talk to the press. The only one who accepted was Alexander, who is also called Adolf, according to Bild. He expressed sympathy for the current German Chancellor, Angela Merkel. His brothers Louis and Brian live together, not far from him, and their neighbors know their origins and claim to be "excellent people." "You can't be blamed for your relatives," one of their neighbors told the German daily. As everyone is entitled to their own opinion, I want to say that just as many others have said, they should not be held accountable for any of Hitler’s wrongdoings.

response.answer_text: There are no direct descendants of Adolf Hitler alive today and only a few remaining descendants of his father, Alois. Hitler had three siblings who survived into adulthood, his half-siblings, Angela and Alois Jr,: and his youngest, full sister, Paula. All four of Hitler’s other siblings—all full blood brothers—died in infancy or very young childhood of infectious disease, probably diptheria, which killed many Austrian children during the 19th and early 20th Centuries. Both Alois Jr. and Angela had offspring. One of Alois Jr.’s son died serving on the Eastern Front in WWII. Another, William Patrick Hitler, immigrated to the U.S. with his Irish mother, served in the U.S. Navy, and had three sons. None of them had any children. Perhaps Hitler’s most famous relative was Angela’s daughter, Geli, with whom Hitler was rumored to have had an intimate relationship. She committed suicide in his Munich apartment in the 20’s, paving the way for Eva Braun’s emergence. Several of Hitler’s cousins, with whom he had little to no contact, were arrested by the Soviets at the end of World War II and taken to the Soviet Union. Some died there. His sister Paula survived the war, but died in 1960 (I think) without ever having had children. Today, there are a handful of known descendants of Alois still alive, all elderly and all childless. The most prominent is probably Hitler’s grand nephew, Heiner Hochegger, who lives in Austria and bears a remarkable likeness to his infamous relative. Heiner is Angela’s grandson and the nephew of the late Geli. So that pretty much does it for Alois’s direct bloodline. A combination of deaths by disease, war, and suicide killed many of them, and others chose for whatever reasons not to have kids themselves. Contrary to widely reported speculation that William Patrick Hitler’s three children had formed an agreement to not have children, so that Hitler’s genes would die with them, the youngest denied this. But that only accounts for Hitler’s direct paternal relatives from his father’s generation on down. His mother Klara, had five siblings, and Hitler had numerous relatives on his mother’s side, including several of the cousins the Soviets imprisoned. Klara’s parents also had siblings and they had offspring. His grandmother Maria’s maiden name had been Shickelgruber, and there were (and are) numerous people with that name near Linz, Austria. Moreover, Hitler’s paternal grandfather, Johann Hiedler, married Maria when Alois was already five. He gave his name (Hiedler/Hitler) to Alois and claimed parentage, but this is widely disputed and a not uncommon accommodation at the time to confer legitimacy. There’s lot of speculation as to who Hitler’s grandfather really was, with Johann’s brother being the most likely candidate. Interestingly, Klara Hitler, nee Polzl, was also a direct descendant of this brother, meaning that Klara and Alois were distant cousins. Regardless, the point is that both on Klara’s side and from descendants of older generations, there are still numerous people alive today who share ancestry with Hitler no more than 4 generations back; enough for a commercial DNA test to make the connection. Some of these probably have no idea. Others, for obvious reasons, are not keen on public exposure and have never come forward to talk about it.

Hitler had no children.His younger sister, Paula, died in 1960. She had no children.His other four siblings died in childhood.Angela Hammitzsch nee Hitler, Hitler's elder half-sister, died in 1949. She had three children:Leo Raubal (1906-1977), Adolf Hitler's nephew. Hitler liked him. Leo served in Luftwaffe, injured in January 1943 during a battle of Stalingrad. Paulus asked Hitler for a plane to evacuate him, but Hitler refused. On January 31, 1943, Leo had been captured by the Soviets. Hitler wanted to exchange him for Stalin's son, Yakov, but Stalin refused. As a result, Yakov commited a suicide, and Leo spent 12 years in Soviet jails. He was released in 1955.Peter Raubal (born in 1931) was Leo's son, and Adolf Hitler's grandnephew. It is not clear whether he is still alive, and whether he has/had children. Maybe he changed his name.Angela "Geli" Raubal (1908-1931), Adolf Hitler's niece. He declared her the only woman he ever loved. He was posessive of her, and abused her sexually and psychologically. She wanted to escape to Vienna, but Hitler did not allow her. In 1931 she commited a suicide.Elfriede Maria Hochegger (Raubal) (1910-1993), Adolf Hitler's niece. Her only son, Heiner Hochegger (1945-1949), died at the age of 4.Alois Matzelberger Hitler (1882-1956) (not to be confused with his and Adolf's father, Alois Hitler Sr.) was Hitler's half-brother. He was never close with Hitler, and seemed to be uninterested in political issues. In 1896, at 14, he left home for, Dublin, Ireland, due to increasingly violent arguments with his father, Alois Hitler Sr. and apparently strained relations with his stepmother Klara. After working as an apprentice waiter, he was arrested for theft and served a five-month sentence in 1900, followed by an eight-month sentence in 1902. In 1910, he married Bridget Dowling. The couple settled in Liverpool, in 1911 they had a son. He tried to run small businesses, to no avail. In 1914, he left his family and returned alone to Germany, where in 1916 he married another woman, because somebody told him Bridget is dead. In 1924, he was tried for bigamy, but Bridget intervened on his behalf, and he was acquitted. In 1934, he established a restaurant which became popular. He ran it during the war. At the end of the war he was arrested by the British but released when it became clear he had played no role in his half-brother’s regime. He died in a traffic accident at the age of 74. He had two sons:William Patric Hitler (1911-1987), Hitler's nephew, changed his name to Stuart-Houston. In 1939, he told he hates his uncle. From the age of 3, he was raised by his mother in Ireland. In 1933, William returned to Germany, hoping to benefit from his uncle's raise to power. He only got jobs of a car salesman and such. He tried to blackmail Hitler, threatening to disclose embarassing family stories to the mass media, but it wasn't really successful. In 1939, he left to the USA, together with his mother. During the WWII, he served in U.S. Navy as a Pharmacist's Mate, receiving the Purple Heart. In 1947, he was discharged, changed his name to Stuart-Houston, married (his wife was born in Germany in mid-1920s), and established a laboratory which analysed blood samples for hospitals. He had 4 children:Alexander Adolf (b. 1949), Louis (b. 1951), Howard Ronald (1957–1989), and Brian William (b. 1965) Stuart-Houston, are Hitler's grandnephews. Alexander, Louis, and Brian William are still alive.Heinrich "Heinz" Hitler (1920-1942), Hitler's nephew, was raised in Germany, so, quite expectedly, he was a devoted Nazi. He attended an elite military academy, joined the Wehrmacht, and was captured by the Soviets in January 1942. After several days of interrogations and tortures, he died in Butyrka (Moscow military prison).We don't know who was Hitler's paternal grandfather, so Hitler may theoretically have alive cousins (but it is very improbable that they are still alive), or their descendands, which is much more believable.Sources: wikipedia, geni.com, WW2 Gravestone .

Paula Hitler was the last surviving member of Hitler's immediate family when she died in 1960. He also had a half-brother (same father, different mother) Alois Hitler, who lived for a time in Liverpool and then returned to Germany where he ran a restaurant throughout WW2. Alois had two children: William Patrick Hitler and Heinz Hitler. Heinz Hitler joined the Wehrmacht and served on the eastern front, where he was captured and died in prison in 1942. William Patrick Hitler was brought up in Liverpool, tried to benefit from the Nazi rise to power, failed to do so and left for the USA, where he served in the US Navy during WW2. He had children, some of whom are still alive and living in the USA. Angela Hitler was Adolf Hitler's half-sister. Angela was the mother of Geli Raubal, who was possibly romantically involved with Adolf Hitler before her alleged suicide in 1931. Angela's son, Leo Raubal fought on the Eastern Front, was captured at Stalingrad but survived the war, and had children, who are still alive. There have also been claims that there are persons less-closely related (e.g. matched by DNA) living in Austria, mostly they have changed their names. e.g. this article: http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1213589/Hitlers-secret-family-How-researchers-tracked-39-living-descendants-dictator.html More details: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hitler_family
